    <div class="mb-8"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_results" %></div>

    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Hourly to Salary Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Select your conversion direction: either hourly rate to salary or annual salary to hourly rate. Enter the amount, then customize the hours per week and weeks per year to match your actual work schedule. The calculator instantly converts your input into all six pay periods: hourly, daily, weekly, biweekly, monthly, and annual. This gives you a complete picture of your compensation from a single number.
      </p>
      <p>
        The bidirectional design makes this tool especially useful when comparing job offers. If one position pays $28 per hour and another offers $55,000 annually, you can quickly convert both to the same basis for a fair comparison. The customizable hours and weeks settings ensure the comparison reflects your real working conditions, not just a theoretical 2,080-hour year.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Hourly vs. Salary: Key Differences</h2>
      <p>
        The distinction between hourly and salaried compensation goes beyond just the pay structure. Hourly employees are typically paid for every hour worked and receive overtime for hours exceeding 40 per week. Salaried employees receive a fixed amount regardless of hours, and many are classified as exempt from overtime. Understanding these differences is crucial when evaluating job offers and negotiating compensation.
      </p>

      <h3>The 2,080-Hour Standard</h3>
      <p>
        The number 2,080 comes from multiplying 40 hours per week by 52 weeks per year. This is the standard assumption for full-time annual work hours. However, many workers do not actually work all 52 weeks. Paid vacation, sick leave, and holidays effectively reduce the actual working weeks. If you have 2 weeks of paid vacation and 10 paid holidays, your effective working time is about 49 weeks, though your salary still covers the full 52. This is why salaried positions with good benefits can be more valuable than they initially appear when compared to hourly rates.
      </p>

      <h3>When to Choose Hourly Over Salary</h3>
      <p>
        Hourly pay is advantageous when you regularly work overtime, because you are compensated for every extra hour at a premium rate. It also provides flexibility for those who want to control their schedule. Salaried positions offer income stability, often come with better benefits, and may provide career advancement opportunities. The best choice depends on your work style, financial needs, and the specific opportunities available to you.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How do I convert an hourly rate to an annual salary?</h3>
      <p>
        Multiply your hourly rate by hours per week and weeks per year. For standard full-time: hourly rate x 40 x 52. For example, $25/hour = $52,000 per year.
      </p>

      <h3>How do I convert an annual salary to an hourly rate?</h3>
      <p>
        Divide your annual salary by total working hours per year. For standard full-time: salary / 2,080. For example, $60,000 / 2,080 = $28.85 per hour.
      </p>

      <h3>What hours and weeks per year should I use?</h3>
      <p>
        Standard full-time is 40 hours per week and 52 weeks per year. Reduce weeks for unpaid leave and adjust hours for part-time schedules.
      </p>

      <h3>How does this differ from a salary converter?</h3>
      <p>
        This calculator focuses specifically on the hourly-to-salary and salary-to-hourly conversion with a direction toggle. A salary converter accepts any pay period as input.
      </p>

      <h3>Should I factor in benefits when comparing hourly vs salary?</h3>
      <p>
        Yes. Benefits like health insurance, retirement matching, and paid time off can add 20-40% to the value of a salaried position. Factor these in for an accurate comparison.
      </p>

